{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"35d12deb-32e3-4687-830d-a156754fceff","content":"Use **`dotnet workload update`**.\n\n- **`dotnet workload update`** — Downloads the **latest versions** of all installed workloads, matching them to your current SDK. This is exactly what you need after an SDK update, since your existing workload versions may no longer be compatible.\n\n- **`dotnet workload repair`** — Reinstalls workloads at their **current versions**. It fixes corrupted or incomplete installs but won't pull newer versions to match a new SDK.\n\n**TL;DR:** After an SDK update, run:\n\n```bash\ndotnet workload update\n```\n\nIf the build still fails after that, also try `dotnet workload repair` to rule out a corrupted install.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"2ff92eac-f738-41cc-9d05-ab34bd895b77","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about .NET MAUI workload management - specifically whether to use `dotnet workload update` or `dotnet workload repair` after a .NET SDK update broke their build.\n\nThis is a general knowledge question, not a codebase-specific task. I can answer directly.\n\n**`dotnet workload update`** — Downloads and installs the latest versions of all installed workloads, matching them to the current SDK version. This is what you want after an SDK update, because the workload versions need to align with the new SDK.\n\n**`dotnet workload repair`** — Reinstalls all installed workloads to fix corrupted or incomplete installations. \n\nThe key difference is that `dotnet workload repair` just re-downloads the existing versions without updating them, so after an SDK update you'd end up with incompatible workload versions. `dotnet workload update` is the right move because it pulls versions that actually work with your new SDK.","outputTokens":403,"requestId":"F40E:2EB5E6:1F5B107:2324BC5:69E81991"},"id":"a4f35c3d-b6a0-4fa1-95e5-e8a4d472633c","timestamp":"2026-04-22T00:43:06.746Z","parentId":"b27c6855-534e-4440-906b-2649b5c37b63"}
